print("The Row echelon form of matrix A and the pivot columns : {}".format(A_rref))

A linear transformation is a particular type of transformation, where one set of vectors is transformed into another vector set using some linear operator.

Let transformation be denoted as T. Then a linear transformation can be written as\begin{align}
T: \mathbb{R}^2 \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^3
\end{align}

where\begin{align}
T \Biggl(
    \begin{bmatrix}
    x \\ y \\ z
    \end{bmatrix}
\Biggr) = 
\begin{bmatrix}
    x + y \\
    y - z 
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{align}

Here transformation T takes in a 3 \times 1 vector and transforms it into a 2 \times 1 vector.

So T(\mathbf{v}) is\begin{align}
\mathbf{v} = 
    \begin{bmatrix}
    4 \\ 2 \\ -3
    \end{bmatrix}
T(\mathbf{v}) = 
    T \Biggl(
    \begin{bmatrix}
    4 \\ 2 \\ -3
    \end{bmatrix}
    \Biggr) = 
\begin{bmatrix}
4 + 2 \\
2 - (-3) 
\end{bmatrix} = 
\begin{bmatrix}
6 \\
5
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align}

Some properties of linear transformations:

T(\mathbf{u} + \mathbf{v}) = T(\mathbf{u}) + T(\mathbf{v})

T(c\mathbf{v}) = cT(\mathbf{v})

In order to check if a transformation is linear, we can use these properties to check if the transformation satisfies these conditions.

Transformation composition can be defined as (T_1T_2)(\mathbf{v}) = T_1(T_2(\mathbf{v}))

The associative property states that when you perform transformation composition on the first of two transformations
and then the result on a third, you get the same result as performing the composition on the last two transformations and then performing the transformation described by the first on the result of those second two.([T_1T_2]T_3)(\mathbf{v}) = (T_1[T_2T_3])(\mathbf{v})

For scalar multiplication no matter where you introduce the scalar multiple, the result is the same.

The additive identity transformation T_0 takes a vector and transforms that vector into a zero vector.\begin{align}
T_0(\mathbf{v}) = 
 T_0 \Biggl(
    \begin{bmatrix}
    2 \\ 3
    \end{bmatrix}
    \Biggr) =
    \begin{bmatrix}
    0 \\ 0
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{align}

The multiplicative identity transformation I when given a vector \mathbf{v} isI(\mathbf{v}) = \mathbf{v}

There are several other properties that could be explored such as tying distribution, scalar multiplication and addition altogether.T(c_1\mathbf{v_1} + c_2\mathbf{v_2} + \dots + c_k\mathbf{v_k}) = c_1T\mathbf{v_1} + c_2T\mathbf{v_2} + . . . + c_kT\mathbf{v_k}

One can make use of matrices to apply linear transformations. For example consider a linear transfromation where\begin{align}
T \Biggl(
    \begin{bmatrix}
    x \\ y
    \end{bmatrix}
    \Biggr) =
    \begin{bmatrix}
    -x \\ y
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{align}

Then you can use a 2 \times 2 matrix A such that\begin{align}
A =
    \begin{bmatrix}
        -1 & 0 \\
        0 & 1 \\
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{align}\begin{align}
T(\mathbf{v}) = 
A * \begin{bmatrix}
    x \\ y
    \end{bmatrix} =
    \begin{bmatrix}
        -1 & 0 \\
        0 & 1 \\
    \end{bmatrix} *
    \begin{bmatrix}
    x \\ y
    \end{bmatrix} = 
    \begin{bmatrix}
    -x \\ y
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{align}

So T(\mathbf{v}) = A * \mathbf{v}

One can get such matrix by writing the transformation as a sum of different vectors of coefficients. For example\begin{align}
T \Biggl(
    \begin{bmatrix}
    x \\ y \\ z
    \end{bmatrix}
    \Biggr) \rightarrow
    \begin{bmatrix}
    y - 2z \\ 
    -2x + y - 3z \\
    x + 3y
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{align}\begin{align}
= x   \begin{bmatrix}
        0 \\ -2 \\ 1
    \end{bmatrix} +
y   \begin{bmatrix}
    1 \\ 1 \\ 3 
    \end{bmatrix} + 
z   \begin{bmatrix}
    -2 \\ -3 \\ 0 
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{align}

Hence the matrix is\begin{bmatrix}
        0 & 1 & -2 \\
        -2 & 1 & -3 \\
        1 & 3 & 0 
\end{bmatrix}

To translate a vector from one point to another point involves performing a transformation that adds a distance vector to the current vector i.e.\begin{align}
T \Biggl(
    \begin{bmatrix}
    x \\ y 
    \end{bmatrix}
\Biggr) = 
\begin{bmatrix}
    x + x_0 \\
    y + y_0 
    \end{bmatrix} \\
A * \begin{bmatrix}
    x \\ y \\ 1
    \end{bmatrix} =
\begin{bmatrix}
    1 & 0 & x_0 \\ 
    0 & 1 & y_0
    \end{bmatrix} * 
    \begin{bmatrix}
    x \\ y \\ 1
    \end{bmatrix} =
    \begin{bmatrix}
    x + x_0 \\
    y + y_0 
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{align}

This operation can dilate (expand) or contract (shrink) the vector based on the distance vector.

To double the magnitude of a vector, the matrix required for the linear transformation D*\mathbf{v} is\begin{align}
D = \begin{bmatrix}
    2 & 0 \\ 
    0 & 2
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{align}

In general the multiplier is across the diagonal and 0s in all other positions of the matrix. If the multiplier is greater than 1 then you have a dilation, if it is between 0 and 1 you have a contraction.
